http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title.value: United States History Since 1890 Curriculum Framework

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: In Grades 5-8, students receive a strong foundation in United States History from pre-colonialism through the Progressive Era, allowing United States History Since 1890 to focus in greater depth on the effects of changing culture, technology, world economy, and environment, as well as the impact of global conflicts on contemporary society in the United States. The desired outcome of this course is for students to develop an understanding of the cause-and-effect relationship between past and present events, recognize patterns of interactions, and understand the impact of events in the United States within an interconnected world. United States History Since 1890 examines the emergence of the United States as a world power to the present. Students will examine the political, economic, geographic, social, and cultural development of the United States of America from the late nineteenth century into the twenty-first century. United States History Since 1890 references the eras and time periods from The National Center for History in the Schools.
Era 7: Emergence of Modern America 1890-1930
Students will evaluate the territorial expansion and foreign policy of the United States between 1890 and 1930.
Analyze social, economic, political, and geographic effects of acquiring new territories on the development of the United States

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., Spanish-American War, annexation of Hawaii

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluate social, economic, and political motives for and impact of the involvement of the United States in World War I using multiple primary and secondary sources
Analyze the historical significance of battles, events, and people during WWI
Investigate social, economic, and technological effects of World War I on American society

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., women's right to vote, new weapons, isolationism, nativism, Dawe's Plan, buying on credit

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine political implications of World War I

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., Wilson's Fourteen Points, Treaty of Versailles, ratification debate

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluate credibility and limitations of primary and secondary sources representing multiple perspectives about the changing role of the United States in the world from 1890-1930
Construct explanations about the changing role of the United States in the world from 1890-1930 and the effects on future eras
Students will evaluate social, economic, and political changes in the United States between 1890 and 1930.
Analyze the relationship between industrialization and immigration/migration in the United States
Investigate the impact of the Progressive Era using a variety of sources and multiple perspectives
Analyze short- and long-term social, economic, political, educational, and environmental effects of progressivism at the local, state, and national levels
Evaluate the effects of the political issues of the 1920s

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., xenophobia, nativism, racism, communism, Open Door Policy, labor movements, equality

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine reasons for and effects of social, economic, political, and cultural changes during the 1920s

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., Harlem Renaissance, Lost Generation, prohibition, Stock Market, medical

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Construct historical arguments and explanations about the long-term impact of social, economic, political, and cultural changes that occurred during the 1920s utilizing evidence from a variety of primary and secondary sources
Era 8: The Great Depression and World War II 1929-1945
Students will evaluate social, economic, and political changes in the United States during and following the Great Depression.
Analyze national and international causes of the Great Depression

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., political decisions, protectionism, speculation, world gold standard, tariffs, unemployment, environment

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze the federal government's fiscal responses to the Great Depression

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., Tennessee Valley Authority, social security, minimum wage, construction projects

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Construct historical arguments and explanations about social, economic, political, geographical, and environmental effects of the Great Depression on various regions from multiple perspectives

Evaluate the changing role of the federal government between 1929 and 1945 and the changing views of Americans toward the role of government from multiple perspectives using primary and secondary sources
Students will evaluate social, economic, and political changes in the United States during World War II.
Evaluate motives for and impact of the involvement of the United States in World War II

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., financial, material, human costs

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine the roles of national and foreign leaders during World War II using a variety of primary and secondary sources
Analyze the historical significance of battles, events, and people during World War II using a multiple sources
Investigate social, economic, and political effects of World War II on the American people from multiple perspectives using a variety of primary and secondary sources

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., rationing, internment camps, contributions of women and minorities, defense industry towns, African-American migration, farmer prosperity, G.I. Bill of Rights, employment of women

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze the impact of advances in science and technology during World War II

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., Office of Scientific Research and Development, Manhattan Project, blood plasma, penicillin, radar, semiconductors, synthetic materials

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluate the credibility and limitations of primary and secondary sources representing multiple perspectives on the social and economic effects of World War II on the American people
Era 9: Post-war United States 1945 to Early 1970s
Students will analyze international events and trends resulting in the emergence of the United States as a superpower.
Examine the results and implications of World War II nationally and globally

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., Yalta Conference, Marshall Plan, international alliances and treaties, nuclear age

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze the origins, developments, and effects of Soviet-American rivalry in the Cold War

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., Yalta Conference, Marshall Plan, Berlin Crisis, international alliances and treaties, nuclear weapons, Cuban Missile Crisis, space race, technological advances, McCarthyism

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze sources of conflict and confrontation during the post-World War II era

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., atomic bomb, Truman Doctrine, Korea, Vietnam, China, Berlin, Afghanistan, Cuba

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Discuss the effects of changes in U.S. foreign policy following World War II from multiple perspectives

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., Africa, Asia, Latin America, Middle East, Soviet Union

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Construct historical arguments or explanations of the effectiveness of international organizations in preventing or resolving conflicts from multiple perspectives
Construct explanations on reasons for the emergence of the United States as a superpower by the mid-1970s using a variety of sources
Students will analyze social, economic, and political changes in the United States between 1945 and 1970.
Analyze the roles of individuals, groups, and the government in securing civil rights during the mid-20th century using a variety of primary and secondary sources

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., minorities, women, NAACP, federal court cases, legislation, Twenty-fourth Amendment

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze causes and effects of cultural changes on society in the United States

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., changing roles of women, forces of change on the nuclear family, suburbanization

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze the technological transformation of post-World War II America

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., communication, information processing, transportation, energy production, medical technology

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine domestic policies of the federal government between 1945 and 1970 and the outcomes from multiple perspectives

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., New Frontier, Great Society, civil rights, social issues

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Construct historical arguments of long-term effects of social and economic changes occurring during the mid-20th century using available data and multiple sources
Era 10: Contemporary United States 1968 to Present
Students will analyze domestic and foreign policies of the United States since 1968.
Examine continuity and change in domestic policies over multiple administrations since 1968 using a variety of primary and secondary sources
Analyze effects of domestic policies on Americans in various social and economic groups

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., inflation, recession, taxes, unemployment, deficits, national debt, financial crisis, economic stimulus

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine continuity and change in foreign policies over multiple administrations since 1968 using a variety of primary and secondary sources

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., policies that resulted from Strategic Arms Limitation Talks/Treaty I [SALT I], Camp David Accords, Oil Producing Exporting Countries [OPEC], Strategic Defense Initiative, Iran-Contra Affair, North American Free Trade Agreement [NAFTA], Japanese markets, Dayton Accords

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine reasons for and consequences of United States involvement in foreign conflicts from 1968 to the present using a variety of sources from multiple perspectives
Construct explanations of change and continuity in foreign policy since the emergence of modern America
Students will analyze social and economic trends of the United States since 1968.
Examine the effects of globalization on the United States

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., regional trade blocks, European Union [EU], NAFTA, international organizations, multinational corporations

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze the effectiveness of citizens, institutions, and the government in addressing social and economic issues at the local, state, and national levels since 1968

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., environmental concerns, deregulation, unemployment, homelessness, medical care, food insecurity

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluate the impact of social, economic, technological, and cultural transformations in the United States from 1968 to the present

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., digital technology, Youth Movement, Equal Rights Movement, economic fluctuations, national debt crisis

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Critique the historical accuracy of a variety of secondary sources on social and economic trends since 1968

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., websites, documentaries, movies, newspaper articles, biographies
